ğŸªœ STEP-BY-STEP CREATION
âœ… STEP 1: Create VPC
CIDR: 10.0.0.0/16
Why? Large IP range for scalability.

âœ… STEP 2: Create Subnets
Public Subnet
10.0.1.0/24
Enable auto assign public IP

Use:
Load Balancer
Bastion
NAT Gateway
Private Subnet
10.0.2.0/24
Disable auto assign public IP

Use:
App EC2
RDS

âœ… STEP 3: Create Internet Gateway
Attach to VPC.
Public route table:
0.0.0.0/0 â†’ IGW
Attach to Public Subnet.

âœ… STEP 4: Create NAT Gateway
Create Elastic IP
Create NAT Gateway in Public Subnet
Private route table:
0.0.0.0/0 â†’ NAT Gateway
Attach to Private Subnet.

Why?
Private EC2 3rd party API access kosam.

âœ… STEP 5: Create Security Groups
Load Balancer SG
80 / 443 â†’ 0.0.0.0/0
Bastion SG
22 â†’ Your IP only
App EC2 SG
3000 â†’ From Load Balancer SG
22 â†’ From Bastion SG
RDS SG
3306 â†’ From App EC2 SG only
Layered security ğŸ”¥

âœ… STEP 6: Create Load Balancer

Use:
Elastic Load Balancing
Place in Public Subnet
Attach LB Security Group
Target Group â†’ Private EC2

âœ… STEP 7: Create Private EC2 (App Server)

Use:
Amazon EC2
Select Private Subnet
Disable public IP
Attach App Security Group
Deploy application here.

âœ… STEP 8: Create RDS

Use:
Amazon RDS
Select Private Subnet
Disable public access
Attach RDS Security Group

ğŸ” COMPLETE TRAFFIC FLOW
User Traffic
User â†’ Internet â†’ IGW â†’ Load Balancer â†’ Private EC2 â†’ RDS

Developer Access
Laptop â†’ Bastion â†’ Private EC2

3rd Party API Access
Private EC2 â†’ NAT Gateway â†’ Internet

ğŸ” SECURITY ADVANTAGES

âœ” App server no public IP
âœ” Database fully private
âœ” Only Load Balancer exposed
âœ” SSH restricted
âœ” Outbound controlled

ğŸ¯ INTERVIEW STRONG ANSWER
"In production, I design a VPC with segregated public and private subnets. Public subnet hosts the load balancer, bastion host, and NAT gateway. Application and database servers are placed in private subnets without public IPs. Inbound traffic flows through the load balancer, while outbound internet access from private instances is routed via NAT gateway. Security groups provide instance-level control, and NACLs add subnet-level filtering."


